2017: Implementation difficulties meant that the project started late, renegotiating the detailed budget with the EU-delegation, which in turn affected the scheduled investments that are seasonally related (for different crops). Now, the project staff team has been completed and the activities have recently started to be implemented, such as coffee plant nurseries and infrastructure to process coffee and beans, as well as some training activities for women and men on gender equality, participation and farming.
2018: 140 hectares of coffee plantations for women have been completed, amongst other types of crops, installations for water capture and reforestation and four climate stations have been built to monitor the weather and help reduce climate change vulnerability. There have been some delays in the project execution due to the difficult context.

2 staff trained on Gender analysis, Environment lens, Financial inclusion and WIMS. Carried out Participatory Rural Appraisal (PRA) for targeted areas and report used to inform planning of interventions. Mobilisation meeting conducted on formation of Housing Cooperatives and as results of this activity, one cooperative was formed with a total of 406 members (181 women, 63 young people and 162 men). The number of women participating in Village Savings & Loans Associations has increased from just 900 to 6,375 with a savings of TZ shillings; 574,828,190. Promoted micro health insurance resulting into a total of 105 members joining (26 women, 63 young people and 16 men).

27 women on the Board, and other key members of 10 local groups, members of RUM, in 9 municipalities have analysed their organisational development and risks, and have created their strategic plan 2019-2023.
30 adult women and 30 young women members have been trained on their rights and have achieved resources for starting up small enterprises through rural credit and savings groups.

150 indigenous and mestiza women in the communities near the buffer zone to the Ecological Reserve Asangni Tawahka have been trained on how to improve their livelihoods in harmony with the care of the natural resources, on women´s rights and indigenous cultural rights.
